# debugonce

**Effortlessly capture and reproduce bugs in your Python code.**

[![PyPI Downloads](https://static.pepy.tech/badge/debugonce)](https://pepy.tech/projects/debugonce)
[![PyPI](https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/debugonce.svg)](https://pypi.org/project/debugonce/)
[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-green.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT)
[![Python Versions](https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/debugonce.svg)](https://pypi.org/project/debugonce/)

---

## ğŸ” Overview

`debugonce` is a Python utility that makes debugging easier by capturing function calls, inputs, and runtime context. With a simple decorator, you can store a snapshot of any function execution and replay it later for consistent bug reproduction.

---

## âœ¨ Features

- ğŸ§  Automatically captures function arguments, environment variables, working directory, Python version, stack trace, file access, and HTTP requests.
- ğŸ“ Saves session data to `.debugonce/` as readable JSON files.
- ğŸ§ª CLI commands to inspect, replay, export, list, or clean captured sessions.
- ğŸ§µ Reproduce bugs consistently with auto-generated `_replay.py` scripts that include the full function implementation and do not require the `@debugonce` decorator at replay time.
- âœ… Robust tracking even in the presence of test-time mocks (file and HTTP access are always captured).
- ğŸ”’ Logging is isolated to `.debugonce/debugonce.log` and never corrupts session files.
- ğŸ§© Arguments are faithfully serialized (strings quoted, numbers as-is) for accurate replay.
- âœ… Minimal setup â€” just decorate and debug!

---

## ğŸ“¦ Installation

```bash
pip install debugonce
```

---
## ğŸš€ Basic Usage

### 1. Decorate Your Function
To capture the state of a function, simply decorate it with `@debugonce`:


```python
from debugonce_packages import debugonce

@debugonce
def divide(x, y):
    return x / y

divide(4, 2)
divide(10, 0)  # This will raise an error and trigger capture
```

### 2. Check the Captured Session

```text
.debugonce/
â”œâ”€â”€ session_<timestamp>.json
â”œâ”€â”€ session_<timestamp>_replay.py
â”œâ”€â”€ debugonce.log
```

---

## ğŸ› ï¸ CLI Commands

### ğŸ” List All Sessions

```bash
debugonce list
```

### ğŸ§¾ Inspect a Session

```bash
debugonce inspect .debugonce/session_<timestamp>.json
```

### ğŸ“¤ Export a Session

Generates a _replay.py file to recreate the captured call, including the function implementation and correct argument quoting:
```bash
debugonce export .debugonce/session_<timestamp>.json
```

### â–¶ï¸ Replay the Session
Executes the _replay.py to reproduce the same error with the same scenario. Exception output is printed to stderr for CLI visibility.
```bash
debugonce replay .debugonce/session_<timestamp>.json
```

### ğŸ§¹ Clean All Sessions

```bash
debugonce clean
```

---

## ğŸ“ Whatâ€™s Captured?

- âœ… Function name and arguments (with correct types/quoting)
- âœ… HTTP Requests
- âœ… File access (read/write)
- âœ… Python version
- âœ… Current working directory
- âœ… Environment variables
- âœ… Stack trace (if an error occurred)
- âœ… Timestamp

---

## ğŸ”§ Advanced Example

```python
from debugonce_packages import debugonce

@debugonce
def fetch_and_save_post(post_id, filename):
    """Fetch a post from an API and save its title to a file."""
    url = f"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/{post_id}"
    response = requests.get(url)
    data = response.json()
    title = data["title"]
    with open(filename, "w") as f:
        f.write(title)
    return title

fetch_and_save_post(1, "post_title.txt")
```

Then run:

```bash
debugonce export .debugonce/session_<timestamp>.json
debugonce replay .debugonce/session_<timestamp>_replay.py
```

